 Social media calls for a shutdown in Diepsloot, following the murder of a police officer, border on incitement to commit violence and can be construed as a criminal offence, according to Gauteng police commissioner Lieutenant General Elias Mawela. On Thursday morning, members of the community took to the streets, using burning tyres and rocks to block roads in the wake of the murder of Detective Captain Oupa Matjie last Friday. https://www.dailysun.co.za/News/residents-blockade-pretoria-n14-with-rocks-and-burning-tyres-20200123 The community believes foreign nationals in the area committed the crime. https://www.dailysun.co.za/News/watch-gatvol-diepsloot-residents-want-the-army-20200123 But Mawela called for calm, saying the law should be allowed to take its course.   Peters said a group of people went to the police station at around 08:00 on Thursday morning, demanding to see the person who was arrested for Matjie's murder.The person is expected to appear in the Randburg Magistrate's Court on Thursday.Public order police will remain in the area.   Source:   https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/police-call-for-calm-in-diepsloot-after-shutdown-threatened-amid-protests-against-cops-murder-20200123 